		<img alt='' src='http://1.gravatar.com/avatar/1377b84d972c6d1f12bd93997c1a49a0?s=42&amp;d=http%3A%2F%2F1.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D42&amp;r=G' class='avatar avatar-42 photo' height='42' width='42' />			<h4>Jenna <span>commented on 2.9.2010</span></h4>
					<p>If you would like it to be rather less unhealthy, you can substitute plain yogurt for most or all of the heavy cream. I just add enough until it looks/tastes right.</p>
<p>And while similar and often confused, butter chicken is a legitimate Indian dish, while chicken tikka masala is a dish created by Bangladeshi immigrants to sell to the British public. It&#8217;s actually the most popular &#8220;restaurant dish&#8221; in Britain, and they export it to the subcontinent, not the other way around. Think of it as the General Tso&#8217;s chicken of &#8220;Indian&#8221; food.</p>
		<div class="clr"></div>
